content:
In CRM Analytics, make decisions today based on forecasts about tomorrow with time series forecasting. A time series forecast takes an ordered series of points and intelligently forecasts the next values. For example, estimate units sold for the next 4 quarters based on the last 5 years of sales.

To create a recipe:

* Use the Time Series Forecasting transformation in a Data Prep recipe to run forecasts based on historical data and seasonality.
* In Columns to Forecast, select which columns to aggregate and forecast.
* Optionally, in Group Rows, select groups to forecast by.
* In Date for Time Series, select a date column and a date grouping.
* In Forecast Period, specify your forecast outlook.

Choose what happens when data is incomplete:

* None (Include all data) uses all data available.
* Last Time Period uses data up to—but not including—the last time period.

Specify length of forecast from recipe run date. More data is predicted if there’s a gap between the dataset’s most recent date and the current period.

Optionally, use More Options to further modify the time series forecast:

* Seasonality: Choose Auto so Data Prep determines the best seasonality for you.
* Model: You can use one of these models (Additive, Multiplicative, or Auto).
* Generate Confidence Interval: To account for errors in forecasts, select an 80% or a 95% confidence interval.

To add the transformation to the Transform node, click Apply. Save the recipe and run it to see forecasts. Each forecast column shows the results for every time period, including the historical ones.
title: Time Series Forecasting in CRM Analytics
